      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gun Control, Ignored</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Doctors Against Handgun Injury executive director Robert Seltzer letter, in response to Oct 18 article, says questions about gun control were raised again in final presidential debate, and again they were not answered</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Questions about gun control were raised again in the final presidential debate, and again they were not answered (news article, Oct. 18). Vice President Al Gore did not even use his full two minutes to address the issue.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Questions about gun control were raised again in the final presidential debate, and again they were not answered (news article, Oct. 18). Vice President Al Gore did not even use his full two minutes to address the issue.</p>
        <p>George W. Bush endorsed ''instant background checks at gun shows.'' But the bill he supports allows gun show sales to be completed within 24 hours even if the purchaser has not been cleared; alternative legislation allows up to three days to complete the check. The difference is significant. While 95 percent of background checks are completed in 24 hours, in the 5 percent of checks that take more than a day, the buyers are 20 times more likely to be a felon or other prohibited buyer.</p>
        <p>ROBERT SELTZER  Executive Director  Doctors Against Handgun Injury  New York, Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
